{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TtckjouEKwZDQfc2cq26rY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the non-default RabbitMQ configuration:\n\n**Non-default elements:**\n1. **Vhosts:** `/app` and `/ops` (only `/` is the default)\n2. **Users:** `app-user` (management tag) and `ops-user` (management tag) — only `guest` is the default user (and `admin` appears to be a custom admin user, replacing or supplementing `guest`)\n3. **Permissions:**\n   - `/app`: `admin` (.*,.*,.*), `app-user` (.*,.*,.*)\n   - `/ops`: `admin` (.*,.*,.*), `ops-user` (.*,.*,.*)\n   - `/`: `admin` (.*,.*,.*)\n4. **Policies:** `/app` has `ha-all` policy configured for high availability with automatic synchronization\n5. **Queues:** `app-queue` on `/app` and `ops-queue` on `/ops`, both durable classic queues\n6. **Exchanges:** Only default exchanges exist across the vhosts\n\nTo restore the default state, I need to remove the custom configuration: delete the `ha-all` policy, remove both queues, delete the `/app` and `/ops` vhosts, and remove the `app-user` and `ops-user` accounts. The `admin` user is tricky—I need to determine if it's a custom user or the default administrator before deciding whether to delete it.\n\nLooking at the current user list, `guest` is missing entirely, which suggests it was either deleted and replaced by `admin`, or it was never created in the first place. In standard RabbitMQ, `guest` exists by default, but in Kubernetes deployments using the RabbitMQ Cluster Operator, the default setup typically creates a custom admin user instead of relying on `guest`.\n\nFor the rollback script, I need to remove the non-default vhosts `/app` and `/ops` along with all their associated queues, exchanges, bindings, and policies, then delete the non-default users `app-user` and `ops-user`. I should also strip the `admin` user's permissions from those vhosts since they'll be deleted anyway. The tricky part is deciding whether to delete `admin` itself—if it's the only admin user, removing it could lock me out, so I need to be cautious about what the true RabbitMQ default state actually is. a pure RabbitMQ default setup has only the `/` vhost and `guest` user with full permissions. Since this cluster has no `guest` user but does have an `admin` user with administrator privileges, I should treat `admin` as the operational equivalent and focus on removing the custom infrastructure: the `/app` and `/ops` vhosts, their associated users (`app-user` and `ops-user`), the HA policy, and all durable queues in those vhosts.\n\nI'll also check for any custom exchanges or bindings that need to be accounted for in the rollback.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":419,"cache_read_input_tokens":31023,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":419},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5710bc0b-3dbd-4c8c-acba-a01da556ad5b","uuid":"4715e4d3-a6d9-471d-bafd-c1388343202a","request_id":"req_011Cc73r3GFxnmNoDTJdW34h"}
